╚═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

NEXUS: "Engineer, basic diagnostics are insufficient for complex failures.
       I need you to learn tcpdump - a packet analyzer that shows the actual
       data flowing through the network. It's like a surveillance system for
       network traffic. With this, no communication is hidden from view."

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

OBJECTIVE
═════════
tcpdump captures and displays network packets in real-time. You can see:
  - Every packet entering or leaving your interface
  - TCP handshakes, HTTP requests, DNS queries
  - The actual content of unencrypted communications

This is the most powerful diagnostic tool for network analysis.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

TASKS
═════

[ ] Task 1: Basic Packet Capture
    Command: tcpdump -i eth0 -c 5
    Capture 5 packets on your primary interface.

[ ] Task 2: Filter by Host
    Command: tcpdump -i eth0 host server -c 10
    Capture only traffic to/from the server. Generate traffic with:
    curl http://server

[ ] Task 3: Filter by Port
    Command: tcpdump -i eth0 port 80 -c 20
    Capture only HTTP traffic (port 80).

[ ] Task 4: View Packet Contents
    Command: tcpdump -i eth0 port 80 -A -c 20
    The -A flag shows ASCII content. Look for HTTP headers!

[ ] Task 5: Capture DNS Traffic
    Command: tcpdump -i eth0 port 53 -c 4
    In another terminal: dig server
    Watch the DNS query and response packets.

[ ] Task 6: Save Capture to File
    Command: tcpdump -i eth0 -w /tmp/capture.pcap -c 50 &
    Generate traffic, then read: tcpdump -r /tmp/capture.pcap

[ ] Task 7: Analyze a TCP Connection
    Command: tcpdump -i eth0 host server and port 80 -c 20
    Then: curl http://server

    Identify these phases:
    - SYN (Flags [S])      - Client initiates
    - SYN-ACK (Flags [S.]) - Server acknowledges
    - ACK (Flags [.])      - Connection established
    - PSH (Flags [P.])     - Data transfer
    - FIN (Flags [F.])     - Connection close

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

KEY OPTIONS
═══════════
  -i eth0    Capture on interface eth0
  -c N       Stop after N packets
  -n         Don't resolve hostnames (faster)
  -A         Show ASCII content
  -X         Show hex + ASCII
  -w file    Write to file (pcap format)
  -r file    Read from file
  -v, -vv    Verbose output
  -tttt      Full timestamp

COMMON FILTERS:
  host X          Traffic to/from host X
  port N          Traffic on port N
  src host X      Traffic from X
  dst port N      Traffic to port N
  tcp/udp/icmp    Specific protocols

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

VERIFICATION
════════════
1. Create a capture file: tcpdump -i eth0 -w capture.pcap -c 30 &
2. Generate traffic: curl http://server && ping -c 2 api
3. Wait for capture to complete

Create a file called 'capture_analysis.txt' with:
  Line 1: How many packets did you capture? (a number)
  Line 2: What protocol did you see for curl traffic? (tcp or http)

Run: ./verify

Success: You can capture packets, filter by host/port, view content, and
understand TCP connection phases.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

